ademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong>Dressmaker’s Treasury will equip you with a range of necessary tools and techniques which every professional must possess for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>It will help you get more confident. You will know how to: </strong></p><ul><li>Choose the right strategy for making a garment after your first meeting with the client;</li><li>Take necessary measurements correctly and prepare and fill out an order form;</li><li>Choose the right basic pattern and adjust it after your client’s measurements with the help of automatic pattern adjustments calculation tables;</li><li>Avoid common mistakes which result in ill-fitting necklines by choosing the right sewing technique.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;5h 16m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-18-rules-of-choosing-the-right-pattern-for-a-top-worn-over-a-corset/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-18-rules-of-choosing-the-right-pattern-for-a-top-worn-over-a-corset/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2017-11-30T17:47:05+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2017-11-30T17:47:05+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2017"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 18. Rules of Choosing the Right Pattern for a Top Worn Over a Corset."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 18. Rules of Choosing the Right Pattern for a Top Worn Over a Corset."><meta itemprop="description" content="We have gone through the main mistakes commonly made by beginners and you are now familiar with my mock-ups and my patterns with integrated shoulder or halter straps"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding and Evening Dresses. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding and evening dresses. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 18. Rules of Choosing the Right Pattern for a Top Worn Over a Corset.</h1><p>We have gone through the main mistakes commonly made by beginners and you are now familiar with my mock-ups and my patterns with integrated shoulder or halter straps. It is time to make a mini-summary of what has been studied and talk about the general rules of choosing cutting and sewing patterns. All these rules are compulsory!</p><p><strong>I would like to devote this tutorial to the general rules of choosing the right pattern for a top with shoulders worn over a corset or an insert for sewing to the corset to imitate a top worn under it. </strong>In other words, I want to teach you how to choose the right pattern from the ones offered in this course to cut and sew things like this.</p><p><strong>I have sketched possible styles of tops with shoulders for wearing with corsets with different necklines (see below). </strong>The blue outlines are the tops, the red outlines are the corsets, and the green lines mark the bust line.</p><p>Versions 1-4 are <strong>tops with <em>narrow </em>straps (5-6cm max). </strong>The choice of sewing pattern is not affected by presence or absence of sleeves.</p><p><strong>Let us go through all possible designs. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2018.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Design 1.</strong></p><p><strong>The foundation is a corset with a neckline positioned above the bust line. </strong></p><p><strong>The corset is worn with a top with narrow straps. The lowest point of its neckline also stops above the bust line. </strong></p><p><strong>In this case, you must cut the top after the pattern of a corset with shoulders. </strong></p><p><strong>Design 2.</strong></p><p><strong>The foundation is the same corset with a neckline positioned above the bust line (it may also reach right down to the bust line) but this time the top has narrow straps and a low neckline. </strong></p><p><strong>There are two ways you can cut the top in this case: </strong></p><p><strong>&nbsp;- The first way.</strong> If your fabric is high-stretch, you can use the pattern with integrated shoulder or halter straps.</p><p><strong>- The second way.</strong> If your fabric is non-stretch, you must use the pattern of a corset with shoulders.</p><p><strong>Design 3.</strong></p><p><strong>It is a corset with a low neckline (to the bust line and below). The top has narrow straps and a modest neckline which does not surpass the bust line. </strong></p><p><strong>In this case, the top must be made after the pattern of a corset with shoulders. </strong></p><p><strong>Design 4.</strong></p><p><strong>Both the corset and the top have low necklines which stop right at the bust line or below it. </strong></p><p><strong>The top is to be made after the pattern with integrated shoulder or halter straps. </strong></p><p><strong>Let us see what you should do when either the corset or the top is cut one piece with <em>wide </em>shoulder straps (6-7cm min). </strong>It does not matter whether you are making a top for wearing over the corset or a corset garment with shoulders and with or without sleeves.</p><p><strong>Design 5.</strong></p><p><strong>If your top has wide straps, then you should use the pattern of a corset with shoulders regardless of its neckline depth and the neckline depth of your corset. </strong></p><p><strong>Design 6.</strong></p><p><strong>Suppose you want to make a corset with a modest neckline which stops at the bust line or above it with integrated narrow shoulder or halter straps. </strong></p><p>It does not matter whether it has sleeves or not.</p><p><strong>In this case, you should use the pattern of a corset with shoulders </strong>because the neckline stops at the bust line or above it.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2018.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Design 7.</strong></p><p><strong>The only case when you must definitely use the pattern with integrated shoulder or halter straps is when you are making a corset with a low neckline and narrow shoulder or halter straps or a similar garment. </strong></p><p><strong>I suppose it is getting clearer. </strong>You can see that <strong>most</strong> corsets, tops, or inserts with shoulders <strong>are made after the pattern of a corset with shoulders. </strong></p><p>There are very few cases when you can use the pattern with integrated shoulder straps.</p><p>You should, however, think it over and account for the elasticity of your fabric to make the right choice between the pattern with integrated shoulder straps and the pattern of a corset with shoulders.</p><p>We will talk about the construction of these patterns later and now you should simply remember these rules to understand the information given in the tutorials to follow.</p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20boat.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Boat-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20strapless.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Strapless Corset with 4 P